2020 North Atlantic Hurricane Season

In this assignment, you are going to utilize the storms data set that comes in the tidyverse package "dplyr". As you may know, storms contains data of tropical cyclones in the North Atlantic between 1975 and 2021 (assuming that you are using any of the recent "dplyr" versions, e.g.Â 1.1.0, 1.1.1, 1.1.2).

In particular, we are going to focus on the 2020 season, taking into account the information, claims, statistics, and details available in the associated Wikipedia entry (link below):

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Atlantic_hurricane_season

2.2 Above Average Season

According to Wikipedia: âThe 2020 season was a well-above average activity season.â

#Pull out the storms per year and their categories
categories = select(storms, year, category)

#Count the number of storms per year
counts = categories |>  count(year)

#Calculate the average number of storms per year
#This will be used later to compare to 2020 in the graph!
vector_n = unlist(select(counts,n))
avg_num_storms_per_year = mean(vector_n)

#Plot the number of storms per year, and for fun separate it by the category of the storm
categories |>
  count(year, category) |>
  ggplot() + geom_col(aes(x = year, y = n, fill = factor(category))) + 
  
  #Add a line horizontal line for the average number of storms per year, to visualize how 2020 compares to the average
  geom_hline(yintercept = avg_num_storms_per_year, color = "blue", linewidth = 1) + 
  labs(title = "Number of Storms per Year, and Category", y = "number of storms")

#As shown in the graph, the number of storms in 2020 well exceeds the average number of storms per year. The average number of storms per year is roughly 400, while for 2020 there appear to have been about 875 storms which is more than double the average!

3.1 Map of Hurricane Seasons by Month

As you know, the official hurricane season in every year goes from June-1 to November-30. It is said that September, historically speaking, is the most active month, followed by August in second place, and October in third place.

Make a graphic to visualize maps, faceting by month, of ALL storms in the North Atlantic during the hurricane season months of all years from 1975 to 2021. Does your plot support the claim about the top-3 most active months?

Important

Hint: We recommend plotting the trajectories of storms with geom_path() instead of geom_point(). An effective use of geom_path() requires an aesthetic group argument. We suggest creating a new ID column that combines the name and year of storms; this ID column can be used for the group argument. How do you add an ID column? Hereâs an example: filtering storms in the 1970s, we could add an id column as follows:

# hint: adding an "id" column for ggplot convenience so that you
# can use it on an aesthetic 'group' argument
storms70 = storms |>
  filter(year %in% 1975:1979) |>
  mutate(id = paste0(name, "-", year))
#Add an ID column for ggplot convenience
all_storms = storms |>
  mutate(id = paste0(name, "-", year))

#Generate map template
map_north_america = ne_countries(continent = "north america", 
                                 returnclass = "sf")

#Plot map and desired storm data
ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data = map_north_america) + 
  geom_path(data = all_storms, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = month, color = month)) +
  theme(panel.background = element_blank()) + facet_wrap(~ month) + labs(title = "All Storms from 1975-2021 by Month")

#As shown in the graphs, the most active months of the year on average seem to be months 9, 8, and 10 in that order. These numbers correspond to September, August, and October respectively, which matches the information given in the Wikipedia article.


3.2 Map of Hurricane Laura (2020)

According to Wikipedia: âLaura made landfall in Louisiana as a Category 4 hurricane.â Graph a map of Lauraâs trajectory that lets you see its path, where it made landfall in the US, and under what category class it made landfall.

Important Hints and Tips

Recall that the category of a storm is determined by the Saffir-Simpson wind scale: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saffir%E2%80%93Simpson_scale

Also, keep in mind that column wind is measured in knots.

Likewise, if you use "rnaturalearth", the function ne_states()âsee command belowâlets you obtain a map of US states that can be added to your continental map with another geom_sf() layer.

ne_states(country = "United States of America", returnclass = "sf")

Review the steps listed in the HTML of instructions (see Sample Tutorial 1). They give you a guideline to mutate() the values in column category, because of ggplot convenience.

#Edit storms data for ggplot convenience
storms_edited = storms |>
  mutate(category = factor(case_when(
    is.na(category) ~ 0,
    category == 1 ~ 1,
    category == 2 ~ 2,
    category == 3 ~ 3,
    category == 4 ~ 4,
    category == 5 ~ 5,
  )))

#Generate map template
#map_north_america = ne_countries(continent = "north america", 
#                                 returnclass = "sf")
map_states = ne_states(country = "United States of America", returnclass = "sf")

#Pull out the data for Storm Laura
Laura = filter(storms, name == "Laura")

#Plot map and data for Storm Laura
map_Laura_trajectory = ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data = map_states) + 
  geom_point(data = Laura, aes(x = long, y = lat, color = category)) + coord_sf(xlim = c(-120, -20), ylim = c(10,60)) + theme(panel.background = element_blank()) + labs(title = "Storm Laura's Trajectory")
map_Laura_trajectory

#Zomed in!
zoomed_map = ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data = map_states) + 
  geom_point(data = Laura, aes(x = long, y = lat, color = category)) + coord_sf(xlim = c(-100, -80), ylim = c(25,35)) + theme(panel.background = element_blank()) + labs(title = "Zoomed-In: Storm Laura's Trajectory")
zoomed_map

#As shown in the graph, Storm Laura made landfall in the US in Louisiana and it made this landfall as a category 4 hurricane. This observation from our map fits with the information from the Wikipedia article.


3.3 Category 5 Hurricanes in October

Make a map showing the trajectories, and their name-year of all category 5 hurricanes that have occurred (been active) in the month of October (among all years 1975 - 2021). To clarify: this map should contain the full trajectory of every category-5 hurricane that has occurred between years 1975 and 2021 during the month of October.

Important Hints and Tips

Review the steps listed in the HTML of instructions (see Sample Tutorial 2). They give you a guideline to get the appropriate data for the requested map.

#Create a table for the category 5 storms across all years
#Define category 5 as winds >= 137 since the wind column in measured in knots.
cat5_ids = storms |>
  mutate(id = paste0(name, "-", month)) |>
  group_by(id) |>
  summarise(
    month = month,
    wind_max = max(wind),
    .groups = "drop") |> 
  filter(wind_max >= 137)
Warning: Returning more (or less) than 1 row per `summarise()` group was deprecated in
dplyr 1.1.0.
â¹ Please use `reframe()` instead.
â¹ When switching from `summarise()` to `reframe()`, remember that `reframe()`
  always returns an ungrouped data frame and adjust accordingly.
#Remove duplicate rows
unique_cat5_ids = cat5_ids |> distinct()

#Create a table that identifies all category 5 hurricanes in October
oct_cat5_ids = filter(unique_cat5_ids, month == 10)

#Now add the id column to the category 5 storms
cat5_storms = storms |>
  filter(wind >= 137) |> 
  select(name, year, month, long, lat, wind) |>
  mutate(id = paste0(name, "-", month)) |>
  group_by(id)

#Now grab the data for October, Category 5 Storms
oct_cat5_storms = semi_join(cat5_storms, oct_cat5_ids)
Joining with `by = join_by(month, id)`
#Grab the entire storm path for a nicer map!
full_paths = storms |> filter(name == "Mitch" | name == "Wilma" | name == "Matthew" | name == "Michael")

#Set up table for Label Names
ids_oct_cat5 = oct_cat5_storms |>
  select(id, long, lat) |>
  group_by(id) |>
  summarise(lat = first(lat), long = first(long))
  
#Plot each storm path
map_north_america = ne_countries(continent = "north america", 
                                 returnclass = "sf")

map_paths = ggplot() + geom_sf(data = map_north_america) +
  geom_path(data = full_paths, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = name, color = name)) + 
  coord_sf(xlim = c(-100, -40), ylim = c(0,60)) + 
  theme(panel.background = element_blank()) + labs(title = "Paths of October Category 5 Storms") + 
  geom_label(ids_oct_cat5, mapping = aes(x = long, y = lat, label = id), size = 2)

map_paths

#Unfortunately I could not figure out how to move the "Wilma" Label to show the "Mitch" Label!
